When is a relation a function?

Clearly it is important to decide if a given equation is a function. Fortunately there are a couple of ways that we can do this. Firstly we can use the definition of a function to see if any value of \(x\) give at most one value of \(y\). For example \[ y = 13x-10 \qquad \mbox{is a function because for every value of } x \mbox{ there is one value of } y \] \[ x = y^2 \qquad \mbox{is not a function since if } x = 9 \mbox{ then } y = \pm 3. \] It is also possible to determine when we have a function by reading off the graphs of the given equation This is sometimes called the vertical line test. The idea is that if we draw a vertical line at any point on the graph of a relation if the vertical line intersects the graph once then the relation is a function, if the line intersects the graph more than once then it is not a function.
